The research under NSF RUI grant DMS-2100912 was in the area of group theory and the representation theory of finite groups. In particular, the project focused on a number of problems that seek to relate the representation theory of a finite group to the structure and representations of certain so-called "local" subgroups, through problems related to a collection of conjectures known as local-global conjectures, which in turn may give more insight into the real-world objects whose symmetries are encoded in these groups and have implications for the various applications of group theory.

The PI worked with several collaborators throughout the course of the grant. She made progress on several of the key conjectures in the area, including the final proof of Brauer's height zero conjecture from 1955, considered one of the very first of the "local-global" conjectures in character theory, as well as an imporant case of the McKay--Navarro Conjecture, a Galois version of a well-known conjecture of McKay. In particular, the PI's work on this project furthered the knowledge in the area about the action of Galois automorphisms on characters and fields of values of characters for groups of Lie type, and added to the list of structural group-theoretic properties that are known to be determined by a group's character table.



Among the key outcomes of the project were:



* the proof of Brauer's Height Zero Conjecture, published in Annals of Math. (2024);
* the proof of the McKay--Navarro Conjecture for the prime 2, proved in a series of papers published in Isr. J. Math. (2022), Proc. Amer. Math Soc. (2022), and a final paper still under review;
* a description of the fields of values for characters in finite classical groups, published in Transform.Groups (2023), and a proof that Jordan decomposition of characters can be chosen uniquely and Galois-equivariant in the case of connected centralizer, published in J. Algebra (2025);
* the proof of the principal block version of Brauer's Problem 21 on bounding the number of characters in a block in terms of its defect group, to appear in Trans. Amer. Math. Soc.;
* the proof of the principal block version of the Hethelyi--Kulshammer conjecture on bounding the number of characters in a block in terms of p, along with height-zero and Galois extensions of the conjecture, published in Algebra Number Theory (2023), J. Algebra (2023, 2024), and Publ. Mat. (2025).



Other key outcomes included results on extending known local-global conjectures to multiple primes, proving consequences of the McKay--Navarro and Alperin--McKay Conjectures, and work on various extensions of Brauer's Height Zero Conjecture. Several of these papers are still under review.

Part of the PI's activities under the RUI grant were to recruit, encourage, and mentor students to pursue undergraduate research projects. She published joint work with two undergraduates on a consequence of the McKay--Navarro Conjecture in Involve; another paper joint with undergraduates is under review; and six addtional students prepared four preprints on their work proving small examples of consequences and cases of the McKay--Navarro conjecture. The PI's student mentees presented at several conferences, including both local and national conferences and worked extensively on their mathematical writing and presentation skills.					Last Modified: 12/01/2024

